					<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>Link to the course's <a href="/wiki/index.php/Statreasoning-001:Main" title="Statreasoning-001:Main">Main Page</a></p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="Definition">Definition</span></h1>
<p>A <strong>sample</strong> is a subset of the <a href="/wiki/index.php/Statreasoning-001:Population" title="Statreasoning-001:Population">population</a>.</p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="Contextualization">Contextualization</span></h1>
<p>If a characteristic of a population is of interest but a comprehensive investigation is not feasible, the investigation can be constrained to a sample. Characteristics determined for the sample are then applied to the <a href="/wiki/index.php/Statreasoning-001:Population" title="Statreasoning-001:Population">population</a>. How the features of a sample and its analysis affect the accuracy of this inference can be assessed by statistical reasoning.</p>

